<p>Sample size is the number of observations or individuals included in a s=
tudy or experiment. It is the number of individuals, items, or data points =
selected from a larger population to represent it statistically. The sample=
 size is a crucial consideration in research because it directly impacts th=
e reliability and extent to which you can generalize those findings to the =
larger population.</p><p>A larger sample size can potentially enhance the p=
recision of estimates, leading to a narrower <a href=3D"https://www.courser=
a.org/articles/what-is-margin-of-error" target=3D"_self" rel=3D"">margin of=
 error</a>. In other words, the results from a larger sample will likely be=
 closer to the true population parameter. A larger sample size can also inc=
rease the power of a statistical test. This means that with a larger sample=
, you are less likely to find results that are not actually true.</p><div c=
lass=3D"rc-ArticleHighlight cds"><div class=3D"css-1jke4yk"><div class=3D"c=
ss-1t29d8p"><div class=3D"css-sekxls"><div><h3>How to calculate margin of e=
rror for a sample</h3><p>You can calculate your margin of error based on yo=
ur sample size and other measures within your data, such as the sample prop=
ortion. When you have a sample size above 30, you use the equation below:&n=
bsp;</p><p>
</p><p><b>Margin of error</b> =3D Z x sqrt(p(1-p) / n)</p><p>
</p><p>In the above equation, <b>Z</b> is your critical value, <b>p</b> is =
your sample proportion, and <b>n</b> is your sample size. By adding and sub=
tracting this value from your sample statistic, you can create a confidence=
 interval, which measures how certain you are that the true population valu=
e falls in your estimated interval.</p></div></div></div><div class=3D"css-=
